College student Riya put up an online ad to sell her old phone. A few hours later, she got a message from a "buyer" who expressed interest and agreed to make an instant UPI payment. She received a QR code from the buyer, who told her to scan it in order to "receive" the money. Riya scanned the code and input her UPI PIN, following the directions. Rather than getting paid, her account was debited ₹10,000.
The following steps are usually involved in this kind of fraud.
Pretending to be a buyer or customer, the con artist contacts the victim.
They foster trust and create a sense of urgency (e.g., quick payment offer).
They send a payment request or a QR code.
The victim is tricked into inputting their UPI PIN.
The con artist acquires money right away.
Due to their frequent use of digital platforms and potential ignorance of UPI security procedures, college students and online vendors are frequently targeted.
Financial loss, psychological strain, and a decline in confidence in online systems are among the repercussions. since digital transactions are often immediate and irreversible, victims may also find it difficult to get their money back.

Section B: Prevention Checklist: Keep Yourself Safe Online
For Indian College Students
1. Never give out your UPI PIN to anyone, even if they represent as workers at banks 
Keep in mind that scanning a QR code is used to pay, not to receive money 
Always check payment requests before approving them 
Refrain from opening dubious attachments or clicking on unknown links 
Turn on two-factor authentication on all significant accounts 
Create strong, one-of-a-kind passwords for various platforms
2. Avoid using public Wi-Fi for financial transactions 
Check your bank statements frequently for unauthorized transactions 
Install apps only from reliable sources like official app stores 
Don't share confidential data (OTP, Aadhaar, bank details) over calls or messages
* UPI and Financial Safety Advice:
Before sending money, make sure the recipient's UPI ID is correct.
Never "receive" anything by entering your UPI PIN. 

Section C: Introspection (100–150 words)
The thing that shocked me the most during my research on this subject was how easy tricks, like sending a QR code, can result in large financial losses. Instead of using cutting-edge technology, many scams take advantage of people's ignorance and sense of urgency. I discovered that even well-educated users, such as college students, are susceptible to falling for these kinds of scams.
Being more cautious before approving any online transaction is one habit I will personally break. In the past, I didn't always verify payment requests or recognize the distinction between sending and receiving money through UPI. I will now carefully check every transaction detail and make sure I am making a payment before entering my UPI PIN. This knowledge can help avoid needless financial risks.
